{"title_page": "Guy Katz", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=November 2015}}\n\n'''Guy Katz''' (born 12 May 1982) is a German professor, writer, and businessman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fom.de/2014/april/professorenwuerde-fuer-dr-guy-katz.html|title=Professorenw\u00fcrde f\u00fcr Dr. Guy Katz \"April 2014\" FOM Hochschule|publisher=Fom.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/experten/katz|title=Guy Katz \u2013 Politik-Experten|language=de|publisher=Focus.de|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guykatz.com/dr-guy-katz|title=Guy Katz profile|website=Katz Consulting|language=de|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nKatz's [[dissertation]] \"Intercultural Negotiation \u2013 the Unique Case of Germany and Israel\"<ref>{{Cite book|title = Intercultural Negotiation: The Unique Case of Germany and Israel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l_QAOvoZlYEC|publisher=Books on Demand|date=1 January 2011|isbn=9783842348103|first=Guy|last=Katz}}</ref> is considered the first research in the field of [[intercultural relations]] regarding German-Israeli business negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/article/view/id/11892|title=Studienwerk  Der erste Stipendiatine|publisher=Juedische-allgemeine.de|date=15 December 2011|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ism.bwl.uni-muenchen.de/personen/halloffame/katz/index.html|title=Prof. Dr. Guy Katz \u2013 Strategische Unternehmensf\u00fchrung|publisher=Ism.bwl.uni-muenchen.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> He also received a scholarship from \"Ernst-Ludwig-Ehrlich-Studienwerks (ELES)\" for outstanding research.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Studienwerk: Der erste Stipendiat|url=http://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/article/view/id/11892|website=juedische-allgemeine.de|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref> Katz speaks regularly at German-Israeli events,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bayern.landtag.de/aktuelles/veranstaltungen/gaeste-und-begegnungen/28012015-2-studientag-israel-im-bayerischen-landtag|title=Studientag Israel im Bayerischen Landtag|publisher=Bayern.landtag.de|date=28 January 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Freiburg: Kurz gemeldet \u2013 badische-zeitung.de|url=http://www.badische-zeitung.de/freiburg/kurz-gemeldet-xd5nsdeqx--113797444.html|website=badische-zeitung.de|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> has accompanied various delegations to Israel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fom.de/2014/juli/ilse-aigner-zu-gast-in-israel-prof-dr-katz-stellt-kontakte-zu-start-ups-her.html|title=Ilse Aigner zu Gast in Israel: Prof. Dr. Katz stellt Kontakte zu Start-ups her|publisher=Fom.de|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> and is the founder of the [[Bavaria]]n-Israeli Partnership accelerator, a joint initiative of the two countries which allows intercultural entrepreneurial teamwork.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stmwi.bayern.de/service/veranstaltungen/aktuelle-veranstaltungen/veranstaltung/pm/37390|title=Bayerns Wirtschaftsstaatssekret\u00e4r Franz Josef Pschierer beim Start des Bavaria Israel Partnership Accelerator: Wirtschaftsministerium Bayern|publisher=Stmwi.bayern.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bip-accelerator.com|title=Bavaria Israel Partnership Accelerator &#124; Promoting Open Innovation between Companies and Entrepreneurial Individuals in Bavaria and Israel|publisher=Bip-accelerator.com|date=20 June 2014|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nKatz served as a board member for the Jewish community of Munich and Upper Bavaria in the period 2012-2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ikg-m.de/gemeinde/organe|title=Israelitische Kultusgemeinde M\u00fcnchen und Oberbayern|publisher=Ikg-m.de|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Guy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Munich University of Applied Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli male writers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n{{Israel-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=November 2015}}\n\n'''Guy Katz''' (born 12 May 1982) is a German professor, writer, and businessman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fom.de/2014/april/professorenwuerde-fuer-dr-guy-katz.html|title=Professorenw\u00fcrde f\u00fcr Dr. Guy Katz \"April 2014\" FOM Hochschule|publisher=Fom.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/experten/katz|title=Guy Katz \u2013 Politik-Experten|language=de|publisher=Focus.de|date=21 July 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guykatz.com/dr-guy-katz|title=Guy Katz profile|website=Katz Consulting|language=de|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nKatz's [[dissertation]] \"Intercultural Negotiation \u2013 the Unique Case of Germany and Israel\"<ref>{{Cite book|title = Intercultural Negotiation: The Unique Case of Germany and Israel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l_QAOvoZlYEC|publisher=Books on Demand|date=1 January 2011|isbn=9783842348103|first=Guy|last=Katz}}</ref> is considered the first research in the field of [[intercultural relations]] regarding German-Israeli business negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/article/view/id/11892|title=Studienwerk  Der erste Stipendiatine|publisher=Juedische-allgemeine.de|date=15 December 2011|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ism.bwl.uni-muenchen.de/personen/halloffame/katz/index.html|title=Prof. Dr. Guy Katz \u2013 Strategische Unternehmensf\u00fchrung|publisher=Ism.bwl.uni-muenchen.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> He also received a scholarship from \"Ernst-Ludwig-Ehrlich-Studienwerks (ELES)\" for outstanding research.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Studienwerk: Der erste Stipendiat|url=http://www.juedische-allgemeine.de/article/view/id/11892|website=juedische-allgemeine.de|accessdate=18 January 2016}}</ref> Katz speaks regularly at German-Israeli events,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bayern.landtag.de/aktuelles/veranstaltungen/gaeste-und-begegnungen/28012015-2-studientag-israel-im-bayerischen-landtag|title=Studientag Israel im Bayerischen Landtag|publisher=Bayern.landtag.de|date=28 January 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Freiburg: Kurz gemeldet \u2013 badische-zeitung.de|url=http://www.badische-zeitung.de/freiburg/kurz-gemeldet-xd5nsdeqx--113797444.html|website=badische-zeitung.de|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> has accompanied various delegations to Israel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fom.de/2014/juli/ilse-aigner-zu-gast-in-israel-prof-dr-katz-stellt-kontakte-zu-start-ups-her.html|title=Ilse Aigner zu Gast in Israel: Prof. Dr. Katz stellt Kontakte zu Start-ups her|publisher=Fom.de|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> and is the founder of the [[Bavaria]]n-Israeli Partnership accelerator, a joint initiative of the two countries which allows intercultural entrepreneurial teamwork.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stmwi.bayern.de/service/veranstaltungen/aktuelle-veranstaltungen/veranstaltung/pm/37390|title=Bayerns Wirtschaftsstaatssekret\u00e4r Franz Josef Pschierer beim Start des Bavaria Israel Partnership Accelerator: Wirtschaftsministerium Bayern|publisher=Stmwi.bayern.de|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bip-accelerator.com|title=Bavaria Israel Partnership Accelerator &#124; Promoting Open Innovation between Companies and Entrepreneurial Individuals in Bavaria and Israel|publisher=Bip-accelerator.com|date=20 June 2014|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nKatz served as a board member for the Jewish community of Munich and Upper Bavaria in the period 2012-2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ikg-m.de/gemeinde/organe|title=Israelitische Kultusgemeinde M\u00fcnchen und Oberbayern|publisher=Ikg-m.de|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Guy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Munich University of Applied Sciences faculty]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli male writers]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n{{Israel-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy_Katz"}
{"title_page": "Helen Boyle", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish-British physician and psychologist}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr Helen Boyle\n| image              = Dr Helen Boyle.jpg\n| alt                = Photograph of Dr Helen Boyle\n| caption            = Photograph of Dr Helen Boyle\n| alma_mater         = [[London School of Medicine for Women]]\n| known_for          = First woman president of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]\n| birth_name         = Alice Helen Anne Boyle\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year|1869}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]]\n| death_date         = {{Death year and age|1957|1869}}\n| death_place        = [[Pyecombe]], [[West Sussex]], England\n| occupation         = [[psychiatrist]]<br/>[[general practitioner]]\n| honours            = [[Order of St. Sava]]<br/>[[Queen Elisabeth Medal]]\n}}\n\n'''Alice Helen Anne Boyle''' (1869 \u2013 November 1957)<ref name=RCP>{{cite web| url= https://www.rcpsych.ac.uk/docs/default-source/about-us/library-archives/archives-document-library/archives-dr-helen-boyle-first-woman-president.pdf?sfvrsn=bd43967f_2| type=pdf| title= Dr Helen Boyle of Brighton (1869-1957)| publisher=[[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]| date=June 2011| accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> was an Irish-British physician and psychologist.<ref name=\"HainesStevens2001\">{{cite book|last1=Haines|first1=Catharine M. C. |last2=Stevens|first2=Helen M.|title=International Women in Science: A Biographical Dictionary to 1950|url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwom00hain|url-access=registration|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-090-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwom00hain/page/42 42]\u20133|chapter=Boyle, Alice Helen Anne}}</ref> She was [[Brighton]]'s first female [[general practitioner]], and the first female president of the [[Royal Medico-Psychological Association]] (now the Royal College of Psychiatrists). Boyle had a passion for helping women with mental illness in poverty and used this to begin an era of proper treatment for mental disorders.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHelen Boyle was born in [[Dublin]], Ireland, in 1869, and studied in France and Germany, before moving to England in 1887.<ref name=RCP/><ref name=Argus>{{cite news| url= http://www.theargus.co.uk/magazine/nostalgia/14031882.Nostalgia__One_of_the_most_remarkable_women_ever_to_have_lived_and_worked_in_Brighton_and_Hove_Dr_Helen_Boyle/| title= Nostalgia: One of the most remarkable women ever to have lived and worked in Brighton and Hove Dr Helen Boyle| last=Pierce| first=Lucy| work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]| date= 14 November 2015| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> She studied at the [[London School of Medicine for Women]] from 1890 to 1893.<ref name=RCP/> In 1893, she qualified through the Scottish triple examination which allowed Scottish medical schools to equalise with other schools globally. Boyle became licensed in the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal Faculty of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow]] and completed a [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree in [[Brussels]] in 1894.<ref name=RCP/>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1894 to 1897, Boyle worked as an assistant medical officer at [[Claybury Hospital]], where she focused on [[neurological disorder]]s, as well as the [[Canning Town]] Mission Hospital. During her time in the [[East End of London]], she was shocked by the way patients had to deal with emotional stress.<ref name=RCP/><ref name=Argus/><ref name=WOB>{{cite web| url= http://www.womenofbrighton.co.uk/helen-boyle.html| title= Dr. HELEN BOYLE 1869 - 1957| publisher=Women of Brighton| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=LCH>{{cite web| url= http://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/page_id__9482.aspx| title= Lady Chichester Hospital| last=Gaston| first=Harry| work=My Brighton & Hove| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> While there, she became the first psychiatrist to identify [[bacillary dysentery]] among mental health patients in the facility. Boyle later became the medical superintendent at Canning Town Mission Hospital in the East End of London. As a result of the first hand experience she gained in working with mentally ill women in poverty, she was inspired to start her own facility. In 1897, she moved to [[Hove]], [[East Sussex]], where she and [[Mabel Jones]] set up the Lewes Road Dispensary for Women and Children, a [[GP surgery]] in [[Roundhill Crescent]]. In doing so, Boyle became the first female [[general practitioner]] in [[Brighton and Hove]].<ref name=RCP/><ref name=BM>{{cite web| url= http://brightonmuseums.org.uk/discover/2011/03/01/personality-of-the-month-march-2011/| title= Helen Boyle (1869-1957)| last=Kisby| first=Anna| publisher=Brighton Museums| date=1 March 2011| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=MyB&H>{{cite web| url=http://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/page/city_insights-104| title= Blue Plaque: Dr Helen Boyle| publisher=My Brighton & Hove| last=Drury| first=Jennifer| date= 7 September 2015| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=LCH/>\n\nJones mostly looked over Lewes Road Dispensary which allowed Boyle to move to Brighton to start another hospital. In 1905, Boyle set up the Lady Chichester Hospital in Brighton for women suffering with [[mental diseases]]. The hospital offered free or low cost care in a mostly women environment. This practice was made specifically for the treatment of early mental disorders which was the first facility ever created for that type of treatment. The practice later relocated to Hove, and was founded to counter the problem of mentally ill women being sent to [[History of psychiatric institutions|asylums]].<ref name=WOB/><ref name=Argus/><ref name=BM/> The facility was the only one in Brighton to provide [[inpatient care]].<ref name=NCBI/> Boyle worked at this facility for fifty years and remained an integral part of the practice through location changes and expansions. In 1910, she was the only female to speak during a discussion organised by [[Farquhar Buzzard]] about anxiety, depression and [[cyclothymia]].<ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XSD_ucVR3E8C&dq=helen+boyle+doctor&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= The History of Mental Symptoms: Descriptive Psychopathology Since the Nineteenth Century| last=Berrios| first=G.E.| publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]| date=April 1996| access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> During the [[First World War]], from 1914 to 1918, she worked in [[Serbia]] with the Royal Free Hospital Unit along with [[James Berry (surgeon)|James Berry]], and after the war, she was awarded the [[Queen Elisabeth Medal]] and the [[Order of St. Sava|Order of St.Sava]].<ref name=WOB/><ref name=BM/>\n\nBoyle joined the [[Royal Medico-Psychological Association]] (now the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]) in 1898. After being an active and integral member of the association for years, Boyle became its first female president. In 1955 the association held their spring meeting in [[Brighton]], to commemorate 50 years of the [[Lady Chichester Hospital]].<ref name=RCP/><ref>{{cite web| url= http://bjournal.co/7-historic-brighton-women-you-should-already-know/| title= 7 historic Brighton women you should already know| last=Kis| first=Mark| publisher=B Journal| date=9 March 2016| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> She was also involved in the creation of the Guardianship Society (1913), the [[Medical Women's Federation]] (1917), the International Medical Women's Federation (1922), The Child Guidance Council, and the [[National Association for Mental Health]] (now known as Mind).<ref name=RCP/><ref name=NCBI>{{cite journal| title= A quiet revolution in Brighton: Dr Helen Boyle's pioneering approach to mental health care, 1899-1939.| last=Westwood| first=L.| pages=439\u2013457| date=December 2001| pmid=11811188| volume=14| journal=Soc Hist Med| doi=10.1093/shm/14.3.439}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nIn 1929, Boyle moved to [[Pyecombe]], West Sussex and she died there in November 1957, one day after her 88th birthday.[[Helen Boyle#cite note-WOB-3|<sup>[3]</sup>]][[Helen Boyle#cite note-BM-5|<sup>[5]</sup>]] She was pioneer in mental health care for women.<ref name=WOB/><ref name=BM/> In 2015, a [[blue plaque]] at [[Aldrington]] House was erected for her, and a [[Brighton & Hove (bus company)|Brighton & Hove bus]] has been named in her honour.<ref name=Argus/><ref name=MyB&H/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* [[Queen Elisabeth Medal]]\n* [[Order of St. Sava|Order of St.Sava]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Helen Boyle}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NPG name|id=96349|name=Alice Helen Anne Boyle}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boyle, Helen}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century British medical doctors]]\n[[Category:20th-century British medical doctors]]\n[[Category:History of mental health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:People from West Sussex]]\n[[Category:British women medical doctors]]\n[[Category:British general practitioners]]\n[[Category:British women psychiatrists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Sava]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish-British physician and psychologist}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr Helen Boyle\n| image              = Dr Helen Boyle.jpg\n| alt                = Photograph of Dr Helen Boyle\n| caption            = Photograph of Dr Helen Boyle\n| alma_mater         = [[London School of Medicine for Women]]\n| known_for          = First woman president of the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]\n| birth_name         = Alice Helen Anne Boyle\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year|1869}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dublin]], [[History of Ireland (1801\u20131923)|Ireland]]\n| death_date         = {{Death year and age|1957|1869}}\n| death_place        = [[Pyecombe]], [[West Sussex]], England\n| occupation         = [[psychiatrist]]<br/>[[general practitioner]]\n| honours            = [[Order of St. Sava]]<br/>[[Queen Elisabeth Medal]]\n}}\n\n'''Alice Helen Anne Boyle''' (1869 \u2013 November 1957)<ref name=RCP>{{cite web| url= http://www.rcpsych.ac.uk/pdf/H%20Boyle%20Poster%20Crest%20Final%20A3.pdf| type=pdf| title= Dr Helen Boyle of Brighton (1869-1957)| publisher=[[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]| date=June 2011| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> was an Irish-British physician and psychologist.<ref name=\"HainesStevens2001\">{{cite book|last1=Haines|first1=Catharine M. C. |last2=Stevens|first2=Helen M.|title=International Women in Science: A Biographical Dictionary to 1950|url=https://archive.org/details/internationalwom00hain|url-access=registration|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-090-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/internationalwom00hain/page/42 42]\u20133|chapter=Boyle, Alice Helen Anne}}</ref> She was [[Brighton]]'s first female [[general practitioner]], and the first female president of the [[Royal Medico-Psychological Association]] (now the Royal College of Psychiatrists). Boyle had a passion for helping women with mental illness in poverty and used this to begin an era of proper treatment for mental disorders.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHelen Boyle was born in [[Dublin]], Ireland, in 1869, and studied in France and Germany, before moving to England in 1887.<ref name=RCP/><ref name=Argus>{{cite news| url= http://www.theargus.co.uk/magazine/nostalgia/14031882.Nostalgia__One_of_the_most_remarkable_women_ever_to_have_lived_and_worked_in_Brighton_and_Hove_Dr_Helen_Boyle/| title= Nostalgia: One of the most remarkable women ever to have lived and worked in Brighton and Hove Dr Helen Boyle| last=Pierce| first=Lucy| work=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]]| date= 14 November 2015| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> She studied at the [[London School of Medicine for Women]] from 1890 to 1893.<ref name=RCP/> In 1893, she qualified through the Scottish triple examination which allowed Scottish medical schools to equalise with other schools globally. Boyle became licensed in the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]] and the [[Royal Faculty of Physicians and Surgeons of Glasgow]] and completed a [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree in [[Brussels]] in 1894.<ref name=RCP/>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1894 to 1897, Boyle worked as an assistant medical officer at [[Claybury Hospital]], where she focused on [[neurological disorder]]s, as well as the [[Canning Town]] Mission Hospital. During her time in the [[East End of London]], she was shocked by the way patients had to deal with emotional stress.<ref name=RCP/><ref name=Argus/><ref name=WOB>{{cite web| url= http://www.womenofbrighton.co.uk/helen-boyle.html| title= Dr. HELEN BOYLE 1869 - 1957| publisher=Women of Brighton| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=LCH>{{cite web| url= http://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/page_id__9482.aspx| title= Lady Chichester Hospital| last=Gaston| first=Harry| work=My Brighton & Hove| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> While there, she became the first psychiatrist to identify [[bacillary dysentery]] among mental health patients in the facility. Boyle later became the medical superintendent at Canning Town Mission Hospital in the East End of London. As a result of the first hand experience she gained in working with mentally ill women in poverty, she was inspired to start her own facility. In 1897, she moved to [[Hove]], [[East Sussex]], where she and [[Mabel Jones]] set up the Lewes Road Dispensary for Women and Children, a [[GP surgery]] in [[Roundhill Crescent]]. In doing so, Boyle became the first female [[general practitioner]] in [[Brighton and Hove]].<ref name=RCP/><ref name=BM>{{cite web| url= http://brightonmuseums.org.uk/discover/2011/03/01/personality-of-the-month-march-2011/| title= Helen Boyle (1869-1957)| last=Kisby| first=Anna| publisher=Brighton Museums| date=1 March 2011| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=MyB&H>{{cite web| url=http://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/page/city_insights-104| title= Blue Plaque: Dr Helen Boyle| publisher=My Brighton & Hove| last=Drury| first=Jennifer| date= 7 September 2015| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=LCH/>\n\nJones mostly looked over Lewes Road Dispensary which allowed Boyle to move to Brighton to start another hospital. In 1905, Boyle set up the Lady Chichester Hospital in Brighton for women suffering with [[mental diseases]]. The hospital offered free or low cost care in a mostly women environment. This practice was made specifically for the treatment of early mental disorders which was the first facility ever created for that type of treatment. The practice later relocated to Hove, and was founded to counter the problem of mentally ill women being sent to [[History of psychiatric institutions|asylums]].<ref name=WOB/><ref name=Argus/><ref name=BM/> The facility was the only one in Brighton to provide [[inpatient care]].<ref name=NCBI/> Boyle worked at this facility for fifty years and remained an integral part of the practice through location changes and expansions. In 1910, she was the only female to speak during a discussion organised by [[Farquhar Buzzard]] about anxiety, depression and [[cyclothymia]].<ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XSD_ucVR3E8C&dq=helen+boyle+doctor&source=gbs_navlinks_s| title= The History of Mental Symptoms: Descriptive Psychopathology Since the Nineteenth Century| last=Berrios| first=G.E.| publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]| date=April 1996| access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> During the [[First World War]], from 1914 to 1918, she worked in [[Serbia]] with the Royal Free Hospital Unit along with [[James Berry (surgeon)|James Berry]], and after the war, she was awarded the [[Queen Elisabeth Medal]] and the [[Order of St. Sava|Order of St.Sava]].<ref name=WOB/><ref name=BM/>\n\nBoyle joined the [[Royal Medico-Psychological Association]] (now the [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]) in 1898. After being an active and integral member of the association for years, Boyle became its first female president. In 1955 the association held their spring meeting in [[Brighton]], to commemorate 50 years of the [[Lady Chichester Hospital]].<ref name=RCP/><ref>{{cite web| url= http://bjournal.co/7-historic-brighton-women-you-should-already-know/| title= 7 historic Brighton women you should already know| last=Kis| first=Mark| publisher=B Journal| date=9 March 2016| accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> She was also involved in the creation of the Guardianship Society (1913), the [[Medical Women's Federation]] (1917), the International Medical Women's Federation (1922), The Child Guidance Council, and the [[National Association for Mental Health]] (now known as Mind).<ref name=RCP/><ref name=NCBI>{{cite journal| title= A quiet revolution in Brighton: Dr Helen Boyle's pioneering approach to mental health care, 1899-1939.| last=Westwood| first=L.| pages=439\u2013457| date=December 2001| pmid=11811188| volume=14| journal=Soc Hist Med| doi=10.1093/shm/14.3.439}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nIn 1929, Boyle moved to [[Pyecombe]], West Sussex and she died there in November 1957, one day after her 88th birthday.[[Helen Boyle#cite note-WOB-3|<sup>[3]</sup>]][[Helen Boyle#cite note-BM-5|<sup>[5]</sup>]] She was pioneer in mental health care for women.<ref name=WOB/><ref name=BM/> In 2015, a [[blue plaque]] at [[Aldrington]] House was erected for her, and a [[Brighton & Hove (bus company)|Brighton & Hove bus]] has been named in her honour.<ref name=Argus/><ref name=MyB&H/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* [[Queen Elisabeth Medal]]\n* [[Order of St. Sava|Order of St.Sava]]\n\n==References==\n{