ilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\n[[File:Philippi 20200407 112336.jpg|thumb|Volunteers in [[Philippi, Cape Town]] packing [[CARE Package|food parcels]] to be given out to the needy during the COVID 19 pandemic lockdown. The lockdown had a seriously negative impact on South Africa's economy that hit the poor and unemployed especially hard.]]{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" />\n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/ National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Government COVID-19 website]\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 Government officials' speeches]\n*[https://datastudio.google.com/u/0/reporting/1b60bdc7-bec7-44c9-ba29-be0e043d8534/page/hrUIB Dashboard by Data Science for Social Impact Research Group, University of Pretoria]\n*[https://coronamap.co.za Corona virus map]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 World Health Organization (WHO) COVID-19 pandemic information]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "HeyitsBen", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Natalie Chou", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Natalie Chou\n| image = \n| caption = \n| number = 23\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb =\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = UCLA Bruins\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West]] ([[Plano, Texas]])\n| college =\n*[[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA]] (2018\u2013present)\n| highlights =\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] (2016)\n}}\n'''Natalie Chou''' (born December 22, 1997<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Chou|website=FIBA.basketball|url= https://www.fiba.basketball/world/u17women/2014/player/Natalie-Chou|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>) is an American [[college basketball]] player for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA Bruins]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Growing up in [[Texas]], she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] as a high school senior in 2016.  Chou played two seasons of college ball for the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor Lady Bears]] before transferring to UCLA.\n\n==Early life==\nChou was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], to Quanli Li and Joseph Chou.<ref>{{cite news|title=WBB Signs Impressive Recruiting Class|date=November 11, 2015|publisher=Baylor University|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2015/11/11/WBB_Signs_Impressive_Recruiting_Class.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Her mother played basketball for the [[China women's national basketball team|Chinese national team]] before playing professionally in China. She moved to the United States in the mid-1990's with her husband when he received the opportunity to study abroad at [[Lamar University]] in [[Beaumont, Texas]].<ref name=fuchs>{{cite news|last=Fuchs|first=Jeremy|title=Impressive Lineage|year=2017|website=Time.com|url=https://time.com/collection/american-voices-2017/5028327/american-voices-natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=horn_01212016>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=Barry|title=Nothing comes easy|date=January 21, 2016|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=http://interactives.dallasnews.com/2016/natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> When Chou was one week old, she stopped breathing and was rushed to a hospital, where she was revived. She was diagnosed with [[human respiratory syncytial virus]] (RSV), a condition she no longer has.<ref name=villa_07032014>{{cite news|last=Villa|first=Walter|title=A healthy appetite for life, basketball|date=July 3, 2014|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/11171844/hoopgurlz-hungry-natalie-chou-representing-team-usa-fiba-u17-world-championships|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his master's degree, Joseph moved the family to [[Plano, Texas|Plano]] for his work.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Li became a basketball instructor for kids. Chou's parents' relationship deteriorated, and they eventually separated.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Raised in Plano,<ref name=chou_03262020/> Chou grew up with her older sister Tingting, who was trained in basketball by their mom. As Chou grew older, she became the more talented player, while her sister took after their father and was more into academics.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Chou continued training under Li, but also played on then-[[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Jason Terry]]'s girl's [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) team from sixth through ninth grade.{{efn|Terry played 19 seasons (1999\u20132018) in the NBA, earning the [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award]] in 2009 and winning an NBA championship with the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Mike|title=Mavs fave Jason Terry joining G-League Legends as assistant GM|date=September 18, 2019|website=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/mavericks/news/mavs-fave-jason-terry-joining-g-league-legends-as-assistant-gm|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=fuchs/><ref name=villa_07032014/> Terry first noticed Chou while preparing his daughter and her sixth-grade basketball team.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Judging by her skills, he estimated that Chou was in high school.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Terry was surprised to learn that she was only in sixth grade, and he was curious how her mom learned the NBA drills.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\nChou attended [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West High]], where she was a three-time all-state player.<ref name=waco_06162018>{{cite news|title=Lady Bears\u2019 Chou transferring to UCLA|date=June 16, 2018|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/lady-bears-chou-transferring-to-ucla/article_c59f0207-6876-5cdf-9bef-a7398d5c303b.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] and was one of five finalist for the [[Morgan Wootten National Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=fuchs/><ref>{{cite news|title=McDonald's All American Game names boys and girls finalists for Morgan Wootten award|date=March 3, 2016|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/mcdonalds-all-american-game-names-boys-and-girls-finalists-for-morgan-wootten-award|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Chou was a five-star recruit, and [[ESPN]]'s HoopGurlz ranked her No. 8 in the nation in the class of 2016.<ref name=riddle_04082020>{{cite news|last=Riddle|first=Greg|title=Natalie Chou, a former 5-star basketball recruit from Plano West, is granted release from Baylor and will transfer|date=April 8, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-a-former-5-star-basketball-recruit-from-plano-west-is-granted-release-from-baylor-and-will-transfer/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Some Chinese media outlets called her \"the female [[Jeremy Lin]]\", likely more related to her ethnicity.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Why Jeremy Lin and Jason Terry are rooting for Natalie Chou|date=December 4, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18188723/why-jeremy-lin-jason-terry-rooting-baylor-natalie-chou-women-college-basketball|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=riddle_04082020/> Terry said her play was \"not as flashy as Jeremy\", but praised her fundamentals.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\n==College career==\nChou committed to attend [[Baylor University]], where she and her high school rival, [[Lauren Cox]], helped form one of the top recruiting classes in the country.<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Will hyped Baylor freshmen go from local rivals to perfect pair?|date=November 18, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com.sg/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18058478/baylor-natalie-chou-lauren-cox-go-rivals-teammates-college-basketball|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in [[2016\u201317 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2016\u201317]], Chou played in all 37 games as a [[reserve (sport)|reserve]] and averaged 4.7 points, 2.1 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 1.6 [[assist (basketball)|assists]] per game as the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Lady Bears]] reached the [[Elite Eight]] of the [[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2017 NCAA Tournament]]. She led Baylor with a 42.3 [[three-point field goal percentage]], which ranked sixth in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> She was named Big 12 Freshman of the Week for the period ending December 12, 2016, after scoring a season-high 15 points and making a career high five 3-pointers on six attempts against [[Texas State Bobcats women's basketball|Texas State]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Adame|first=Tony|title=Baylor\u2019s Natalie Chou named Big 12 Freshman of the Week; Lady Bears remain No. 3|date=December 13, 2016|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/baylor-s-natalie-chou-named-big-freshman-of-the-week/article_a6b618eb-8276-50c5-bc35-3f5d5c9bf684.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UCLA Signs Natalie Chou to GIA Scholarship|date=June 15, 2018|publisher=UCLA Athletics|url=https://uclabruins.com/news/2018/6/15/womens-basketball-ucla-signs-natalie-chou-to-gia-scholarship.aspx|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2017\u201318]] season opener, Chou scored a career-high 22 points and added eight rebounds and six assists in a 121\u201362 win over [[Lamar Lady Cardinals basketball|Lamar]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jerry|title=No. 3 Lady Bears Roll to Victory over Lamar|date=November 10, 2017|website=BaylorBears.com|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2017/11/10/No_3_Lady_Bears_Roll_to_Victory_over_Lamar.aspx|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> She was a [[starting lineup|starter]] for the first 21 games of the season before undergoing surgery for a broken bone in her non-shooting wrist.<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=ap_05072018>{{cite news|title=Natalie Chou will transfer from Big 12 champion Baylor|date=May 7, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|agency=AP|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaw/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-will-transfer-from-big-12-champion-baylor/34665327/|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> After missing seven games, Chou returned for the final six games as Baylor advanced to the Sweet Sixteen in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]]. She went scoreless after her return, totaling 35 minutes and shooting 0-for-8 with all but one shot from three-point range.<ref name=ap_05072018/> For the season, Chou averaged 6.7 points, 3.3 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.1 [[steal (basketball)|steals]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> Needing a change of scenery,<ref name=dsouza_01302020>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Dylan|title=Natalie Chou carries on basketball tradition passed on from her mother|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Daily Bruin|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-carries-on-basketball-tradition-passed-on-from-her-mother/|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> she decided after the season to transfer to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> \"[The injury] kind of changed the dynamics of a lot of the relationships, and I didn\u2019t like that kind of pressure,\" she said.<ref name=dsouza_01302020/>\n\nDue to [[NCAA]] transfer rules, Chou sat out a season as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] and served on the [[practice squad]] for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|Bruins]] in [[2018\u201319 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2018\u201319]].<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=nguyen_11042019>{{cite news|last=Nguyen|first=Thuc Nhi|title=UCLA, USC women\u2019s basketball teams will get a boost from youngsters|date=November 4, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-11-04/ucla-usc-womens-basketball-teams-will-get-a-boost-from-youngsters|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Eligible to play in [[2019\u201320 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2019\u201320]], she was expected to boost UCLA's outside shooting after they ranked next-to-last in three-point percentage in the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] (30.6%) and last in three-pointers made per game (5).<ref name=nguyen_11042019/> On January 24, 2020, Chou made a season-high four 3-pointers and scored 18 points in career-high 33 minutes in an 85\u201380 overtime win over [[Washington Huskies women's basketball|Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Vanoni|first=Maggie|title=Natalie Chou raising her game as UCLA women\u2019s basketball team enters toughest stretch|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-raising-her-game-as-ucla-womens-basketball-team-enters-toughest-stretch/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She was a part-time starter during the season and averaged 7.6 points and 3.6 rebounds while making 31.1% of her three-pointers for UCLA, who finished 26\u20135 and ranked No. 10 nationally.<ref name=bolch_03222020/> Their season ended prematurely, however, when the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]] was cancelled due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=chou_03262020/>\n\n==National team career==\nChou helped the [[United States women's national under-17 basketball team|United States under-17 team]] win a gold medal at the [[2014 FIBA Under-17 World Championship for Women|2014 FIBA U-17 World Championship]].<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016/> She also won a silver medal playing [[3x3 basketball]] with the [[United States women's national 3x3 team#2015 U18|2015 U.S U-18 3x3 team]] at the [[FIBA 3x3 U-18 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plano West's Natalie Chou, Team USA win silver in 3-on-3 FIBA tourney|date=June 9, 2015|newspaper=Plano Star Courier|url=https://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/plano-west-s-natalie-chou-team-usa-win-silver-in/article_9a31667a-0ed1-11e5-a839-ef4fb3e21b61.html|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Chou spoke out against the rise in animosity towards [[Asian Americans]] since the spread of the virus which originated in China.<ref name=sherrington_04042020>{{cite news|last=Sherrington|first=Kevin|title=Ex-Plano West star Natalie Chou speaks out against anti-Asian racism fueled by coronavirus pandemic|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2020/04/04/ex-plano-west-star-natalie-chou-speaks-out-against-anti-asian-racism-fueled-by-coronavirus-pandemic/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After flying home following the 2019\u201320 season, she was afraid to leave her [[Dallas]]-area home.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=bolch_03222020/> Although she had been used to being stared at for being a {{convert|6|ft|1|in|adj=on}} Asian female, Chou said the looks were now hateful.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> She felt safer going out wearing clothes with ''UCLA'' on it,<ref name=bolch_03222020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> as she hoped to ease people's fears by showing that she was a basketball player and \"not just a Chinese person [that others] need to stay away from.\"<ref name=sherrington_04042020/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=NatalieChou1|author=Natalie Chou|number=1246201661124685826|date=April 4, 2020|title=Thank you for referencing me in your article ...|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Later that month, Chou posted on [[Twitter]] about her experience, which was followed by a story in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and later her first-person account on [[ESPN.com]]. She attributed the growing resentment towards Asian Americans to the use of the slang term ''Chinese virus'', which she stated was \"disrespectful and ultimately racist\" and created \"unnecessary [[xenophobia]]\".<ref name=bolch_03222020>{{cite news|last=Bolch|first=Ben|title=UCLA\u2019s Natalie Chou talks about racism and being associated with 'the Chinese virus'|date=March 22, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/story/2020-03-22/ucla-natalie-chou-talks-racism-the-chinese-virus|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sherrington_04042020/>  Since 2015, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has recommended to not name infectious diseases after geographic locations due to the negative impact on countries, economies and people.<ref name=chou_03262020>{{cite news|last=Chou|first=Natalie|editor-last=Gobson|editor-first=Charlotte|title=UCLA's Natalie Chou won't stand for anti-Asian racism related to coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/story/_/id/28955666/20|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=chow_03302020>{{cite news|last=Chow|first=Cary|title=Why it is NOT the 'Chinese virus'|date=March 30, 2020|website=The Undefeated|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/why-it-is-not-the-chinese-virus/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> According to Chou, \"It takes literally no effort to call it by its correct name&nbsp;{{nowrap|{{bracket|\u2013 [[COVID-19]]}}}}.\"<ref name=chow_03302020/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://uclabruins.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/natalie-chou/8969 UCLA Bruins bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chou, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor Lady Bears basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plano, Texas\u200e]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Natalie Chou\n| image = \n| caption = \n| number = 23\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb =\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = UCLA Bruins\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West]] ([[Plano, Texas]])\n| college =\n*[[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA]] (2018\u2013present)\n| highlights =\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] (2016)\n}}\n'''Natalie Chou''' (born December 22, 1997<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Chou|website=FIBA.basketball|url= https://www.fiba.basketball/world/u17women/2014/player/Natalie-Chou|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>) is an American [[college basketball]] player for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA Bruins]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Growing up in [[Texas]], she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] as a high school senior in 2016.  Chou played two seasons of college ball for the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor Lady Bears]] before transferring to UCLA.\n\n==Early life==\nChou was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], to Quanli Li and Joseph Chou.<ref>{{cite news|title=WBB Signs Impressive Recruiting Class|date=November 11, 2015|publisher=Baylor University|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2015/11/11/WBB_Signs_Impressive_Recruiting_Class.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Her mother played basketball for the [[China women's national basketball team|Chinese national team]] before playing professionally in China. She moved to the United States in the mid-1990's with her husband when he received the opportunity to study abroad at [[Lamar University]] in [[Beaumont, Texas]].<ref name=fuchs>{{cite news|last=Fuchs|first=Jeremy|title=Impressive Lineage|year=2017|website=Time.com|url=https://time.com/collection/american-voices-2017/5028327/american-voices-natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=horn_01212016>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=Barry|title=Nothing comes easy|date=January 21, 2016|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=http://interactives.dallasnews.com/2016/natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> When Chou was one week old, she stopped breathing and was rushed to a hospital, where she was revived. She was diagnosed with [[human respiratory syncytial virus]] (RSV), a condition she no longer has.<ref name=villa_07032014>{{cite news|last=Villa|first=Walter|title=A healthy appetite for life, basketball|date=July 3, 2014|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/11171844/hoopgurlz-hungry-natalie-chou-representing-team-usa-fiba-u17-world-championships|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his master's degree, Joseph moved the family to [[Plano, Texas|Plano]] for his work.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Li became a basketball instructor for kids. Chou's parents' relationship deteriorated, and they eventually separated.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Raised in Plano,<ref name=chou_03262020/> Chou grew up with her older sister Tingting, who was trained in basketball by their mom. As Chou grew older, she became the more talented player, while her sister took after their father and was more into academics.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Chou continued training under Li, but also played on then-[[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Jason Terry]]'s girl's [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) team from sixth through ninth grade.{{efn|Terry played 19 seasons (1999\u20132018) in the NBA, earning the [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award]] in 2009 and winning an NBA championship with the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Mike|title=Mavs fave Jason Terry joining G-League Legends as assistant GM|date=September 18, 2019|website=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/mavericks/news/mavs-fave-jason-terry-joining-g-league-legends-as-assistant-gm|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=fuchs/><ref name=villa_07032014/> Terry first noticed Chou while preparing his daughter and her sixth-grade basketball team.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Judging by her skills, he estimated that Chou was in high school.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Terry was surprised to learn that she was only in sixth grade, and he was curious how her mom learned the NBA drills.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\nChou attended [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West High]], where she was a three-time all-state player.<ref name=waco_06162018>{{cite news|title=Lady Bears\u2019 Chou transferring to UCLA|date=June 16, 2018|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/lady-bears-chou-transferring-to-ucla/article_c59f0207-6876-5cdf-9bef-a7398d5c303b.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] and was one of five finalist for the [[Morgan Wootten National Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=fuchs/><ref>{{cite news|title=McDonald's All American Game names boys and girls finalists for Morgan Wootten award|date=March 3, 2016|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/mcdonalds-all-american-game-names-boys-and-girls-finalists-for-morgan-wootten-award|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Chou was a five-star recruit, and [[ESPN]]'s HoopGurlz ranked her No. 8 in the nation in the class of 2016.<ref name=riddle_04082020>{{cite news|last=Riddle|first=Greg|title=Natalie Chou, a former 5-star basketball recruit from Plano West, is granted release from Baylor and will transfer|date=April 8, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-a-former-5-star-basketball-recruit-from-plano-west-is-granted-release-from-baylor-and-will-transfer/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Some Chinese media outlets called her \"the female [[Jeremy Lin]]\", likely more related to her ethnicity.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Why Jeremy Lin and Jason Terry are rooting for Natalie Chou|date=December 4, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18188723/why-jeremy-lin-jason-terry-rooting-baylor-natalie-chou-women-college-basketball|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=riddle_04082020/> Terry said her play was \"not as flashy as Jeremy\", but praised her fundamentals.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\n==College career==\nChou committed to attend [[Baylor University]], where she and her high school rival, [[Lauren Cox]], helped form one of the top recruiting classes in the country.<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Will hyped Baylor freshmen go from local rivals to perfect pair?|date=November 18, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com.sg/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18058478/baylor-natalie-chou-lauren-cox-go-rivals-teammates-college-basketball|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in [[2016\u201317 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2016\u201317]], Chou played in all 37 games as a [[reserve (sport)|reserve]] and averaged 4.7 points, 2.1 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 1.6 [[assist (basketball)|assists]] per game as the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Lady Bears]] reached the [[Elite Eight]] of the [[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2017 NCAA Tournament]]. She led Baylor with a 42.3 [[three-point field goal percentage]], which ranked sixth in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> She was named Big 12 Freshman of the Week for the period ending December 12, 2016, after scoring a season-high 15 points and making a career high five 3-pointers on six attempts against [[Texas State Bobcats women's basketball|Texas State]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Adame|first=Tony|title=Baylor\u2019s Natalie Chou named Big 12 Freshman of the Week; Lady Bears remain No. 3|date=December 13, 2016|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/baylor-s-natalie-chou-named-big-freshman-of-the-week/article_a6b618eb-8276-50c5-bc35-3f5d5c9bf684.html|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UCLA Signs Natalie Chou to GIA Scholarship|date=June 15, 2018|publisher=UCLA Athletics|url=https://uclabruins.com/news/2018/6/15/womens-basketball-ucla-signs-natalie-chou-to-gia-scholarship.aspx|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2017\u201318]] season opener, Chou scored a career-high 22 points and added eight rebounds and six assists in a 121\u201362 win over [[Lamar Lady Cardinals basketball|Lamar]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jerry|title=No. 3 Lady Bears Roll to Victory over Lamar|date=November 10, 2017|website=BaylorBears.com|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2017/11/10/No_3_Lady_Bears_Roll_to_Victory_over_Lamar.aspx|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> She was a [[starting lineup|starter]] for the first 21 games of the season before undergoing surgery for a broken bone in her non-shooting wrist.<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=ap_05072018>{{cite news|title=Natalie Chou will transfer from Big 12 champion Baylor|date=May 7, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|agency=AP|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaw/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-will-transfer-from-big-12-champion-baylor/34665327/|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> After missing seven games, Chou returned for the final six games as Baylor advanced to the Sweet Sixteen in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]]. She went scoreless after her return, totaling 35 minutes and shooting 0-for-8 with all but one shot from three-point range.<ref name=ap_05072018/> For the season, Chou averaged 6.7 points, 3.3 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.1 [[steal (basketball)|steals]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> Needing a change of scenery,<ref name=dsouza_01302020>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Dylan|title=Natalie Chou carries on basketball tradition passed on from her mother|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Daily Bruin|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-carries-on-basketball-tradition-passed-on-from-her-mother/|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> she decided after the season to transfer to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> \"[The injury] kind of changed the dynamics of a lot of the relationships, and I didn\u2019t like that kind of pressure,\" she said.<ref name=dsouza_01302020/>\n\nDue to [[NCAA]] transfer rules, Chou sat out a season as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] and served on the [[practice squad]] for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|Bruins]] in [[2018\u201319 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2018\u201319]].<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=nguyen_11042019>{{cite news|last=Nguyen|first=Thuc Nhi|title=UCLA, USC women\u2019s basketball teams will get a boost from youngsters|date=November 4, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-11-04/ucla-usc-womens-basketball-teams-will-get-a-boost-from-youngsters|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Eligible to play in [[2019\u201320 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2019\u201320]], she was expected to boost UCLA's outside shooting after they ranked next-to-last in three-point percentage in the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] (30.6%) and last in three-pointers made per game (5).<ref name=nguyen_11042019/> On January 24, 2020, Chou made a season-high four 3-pointers and scored 18 points in career-high 33 minutes in an 85\u201380 overtime win over [[Washington Huskies women's basketball|Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Vanoni|first=Maggie|title=Natalie Chou raising her game as UCLA women\u2019s basketball team enters toughest stretch|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-raising-her-game-as-ucla-womens-basketball-team-enters-toughest-stretch/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She was a part-time starter during the season and averaged 7.6 points and 3.6 rebounds while making 31.1% of her three-pointers for UCLA, who finished 26\u20135 and ranked No. 10 nationally.<ref name=bolch_03222020/> Their season ended prematurely, however, when the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]] was cancelled due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=chou_03262020/>\n\n==National team career==\nChou helped the [[United States women's national under-17 basketball team|United States under-17 team]] win a gold medal at the [[2014 FIBA Under-17 World Championship for Women|2014 FIBA U-17 World Championship]].<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016/> She also won a silver medal playing [[3x3 basketball]] with the [[United States women's national 3x3 team#2015 U18|2015 U.S U-18 3x3 team]] at the [[FIBA 3x3 U-18 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plano West's Natalie Chou, Team USA win silver in 3-on-3 FIBA tourney|date=June 9, 2015|newspaper=Plano Star Courier|url=https://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/plano-west-s-natalie-chou-team-usa-win-silver-in/article_9a31667a-0ed1-11e5-a839-ef4fb3e21b61.html|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Chou spoke out against the rise in animosity towards [[Asian Americans]] since the spread of the virus which originated in China.<ref name=sherrington_04042020>{{cite news|last=Sherrington|first=Kevin|title=Ex-Plano West star Natalie Chou speaks out against anti-Asian racism fueled by coronavirus pandemic|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2020/04/04/ex-plano-west-star-natalie-chou-speaks-out-against-anti-asian-racism-fueled-by-coronavirus-pandemic/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After flying home following the 2019\u201320 season, she was afraid to leave her [[Dallas]]-area home.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=bolch_03222020/> Although she had been used to being stared at for being a {{convert|6|ft|1|in|adj=on}} Asian female, Chou said the looks were now hateful.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> She felt safer going out wearing clothes with ''UCLA'' on it,<ref name=bolch_03222020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> as she hoped to ease people's fears by showing that she was a basketball player and \"not just a Chinese person [that others] need to stay away from.\"<ref name=sherrington_04042020/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=NatalieChou1|author=Natalie Chou|number=1246201661124685826|date=April 4, 2020|title=Thank you for referencing me in your article ...|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Later that month, Chou posted on [[Twitter]] about her experience, which was followed by a story in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and later her first-person account on [[ESPN.com]]. She attributed the growing resentment towards Asian Americans to the use of the slang term ''Chinese virus'', which she stated was \"disrespectful and ultimately racist\" and created \"unnecessary [[xenophobia]]\".<ref name=bolch_03222020>{{cite news|last=Bolch|first=Ben|title=UCLA\u2019s Natalie Chou talks about racism and being associated with 'the Chinese virus'|date=March 22, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/story/2020-03-22/ucla-natalie-chou-talks-racism-the-chinese-virus|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sherrington_04042020/>  Since 2015, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has recommended to not name infectious diseases after geographic locations due to the negative impact on countries, economies and people.<ref name=chou_03262020>{{cite news|last=Chou|first=Natalie|editor-last=Gobson|editor-first=Charlotte|title=UCLA's Natalie Chou won't stand for anti-Asian racism related to coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/story/_/id/28955666/20|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=chow_03302020>{{cite news|last=Chow|first=Cary|title=Why it is NOT the 'Chinese virus'|date=March 30, 2020|website=The Undefeated|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/why-it-is-not-the-chinese-virus/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> According to Chou, \"It takes literally no effort to call it by its correct name {{bracket|, [[COVID-19]]}}.\"<ref name=chow_03302020/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://uclabruins.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/natalie-chou/8969 UCLA Bruins bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chou, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor Lady Bears basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plano, Texas\u200e]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's basketball players]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActivism:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_Chou"}
{"title_page": "Yang Joon-il", "text_new": "{{Korean name|[[Yang (Korean surname)|Yang]]}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Yang Joon-il\n| image            = Yang_Joon_Il.2019.jpg\n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1969|8|19}}\n| birth_place      = Vietnam\n| origin           = [[South Korea]]\n| instrument       = \n| genre            = K-pop, New Jack Swing, Ballad, Dance pop\n| occupation       = Singer, Songwriter, Rapper, Producer, Author\n| years_active     = 1991\u20131993 <br/> 2001 (as V2) <br/> 2019\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul  = {{linktext|\uc591|\uc900|\uc77c}}\n| hanja   = \u6881\u4fca\u65e5\n| rr      = Yang Jun-il\n| mr      = Yang Chun-il\n}}\n\n'''Yang Joon-il''' (born 19 August 1969), also known as '''Joon-il Yang''', '''JIY''' and '''V2''', is a Korean-American singer-songwriter. Nicknamed the \"G-Dragon of the 1990s\", Yang made his debut in 1991 with a song titled \"Rebecca\". He was active in South Korea from 1991 to 1993 before he was banned to perform on TV. He fled back to America disappearing away from the public scene. He recently gained attention through [[JTBC]]'s ''[[Two Yoo Project Sugar Man]]'', a program dedicated to finding and rediscovering old singers from the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hk.entertainment.appledaily.com/enews/realtime/article/20191207/60351939|title=50\u6b72\u97d3\u6b4c\u624b\u649e\u6a23 \u5c01\u300c90\u5e74\u4ee3GD\u300d\u5f15\u95dc\u6ce8|accessdate=23 January 2020|date=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=koreatimes>{{cite web|first=Anna J.|last=Park|title=Yang Joon-il, a musician living ahead of his time, finally recognized 30 year later|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2019/12/682_280113.html|website=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=19 January 2020|date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=koreajoongangdaily>{{cite web|last=Yoon|first=So-yeon|title=Fans welcome back Yang Joon-il|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3072077|website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=19 January 2020|date=1 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=yonhap>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Bo-ram|title=Return of long-forgotten singer Yang Joon-il brings middle-aged fans to music scene|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191231006300315|website=[[Yonhap]]|accessdate=19 January 2020|date=31 December 2019 }}</ref> As of 2020, he is active in various fields such as fan meeting, book writing, public appearances, lectures, commercials, beauty and fashion related activities.\n\n==Personal life==\nYang was born in [[Vietnam]] during the [[Vietnam War|war]] in 1969 and spent his childhood in Hong Kong, Japan, and South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://star-profile.tistory.com/439|title=\uac00\uc218 \uc591\uc900\uc77c \ud504\ub85c\ud544|date=2019-12-28|website=Star Profile|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Yang emigrated to the [[United States]] with his family at age nine and grew up in [[Los Angeles]]. After one year of dating Yang married a woman who fell in love at first sight in 2006 and the first son was born in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://woman.chosun.com/client/news/viw.asp?cate=C01&mcate=M1001&nNewsNumb=20200264195|title=\uc591\uc900\uc77c\u2026\uc544\ub0b4\uc640 \uc778\uc5f0, \uacb0\ud63c \uc774\uc720 \uccab \uace0\ubc31 \u201c\ud55c\ub208\uc5d0 \ubc18\ud588\ub2e4\u201d|date=2020-02-11|website=woman.chosun.com|language=ko|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n==Career==\nWhen he was in [[Glendale High School (Glendale, California)|Glendale High School]] in LA, he was persuaded to make a debut as an entertainer by the late Hollywood actor [[Soon-Tek Oh|Soon-tek Oh]], who was a member to the same church.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tenasia.hankyung.com/topic/article/2020012937744|title=\u6545 \uc624\uc21c\ud0dd \ub204\uad6c?...\uc591\uc900\uc77c\uacfc \ubbf8\uad6d\uc11c \uae4a\uc740 \uc778\uc5f0 {{!}} \ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544|last=tenasia.hankyung.com|first=Digital|date=2020-01-29|website=\ud150\uc544\uc2dc\uc544 \uc5f0\uc608\ub274\uc2a4|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Yang was a soloist in his high school choir. He took classes at [https://www.jrpowersphilly.com/ John Robert Powers Modeling, Acting Agency & Finishing School] in [[Philadelphia]] to prepare for his debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mk.co.kr/star/broadcasting-service/view/2020/02/191812/|title=\u2018\ubc30\ucca0\uc218 \uc7bc\u2019 \uc591\uc900\uc77c, \ubc1c\ub77c\ub4dc \uac00\uc218 \ub370\ubdd4 \ube44\ud558\uc778\ub4dc...\u2018\ub9ac\ubca0\uce74\u2019 \uc5b4\ucfe0\uc2a4\ud2f1 \ubc84\uc804 \uacf5\uac1c[\uc885\ud569]|website=\uc2a4\ud0c0\ud22c\ub370\uc774|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\nHe entered [[University of Southern California]] [[USC Marshall School of Business|Marshall School of Business]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201912311633093457|title=[\ucf54\ub9ac\uc544\ud0c0\uc784\uc2a4 \ub274\uc2a4] \uc2dc\uac04\uc5ec\ud589\uc790 \uc591\uc900\uc77c, 30\ub144\uc774 \uc9c0\ub098\uc11c\uc57c \uc778\uc815\ubc1b\ub2e4|date=2020-01-01|website=\ud55c\uad6d\uc77c\ubcf4|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> During his studies, he was selected by Lee Beom-hee, who was the famous composer of the day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.issueinfact.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=13883|title=\uc591\uc900\uc77c \ub9ac\ubca0\uce74 \uc2e0\ub4dc\ub86c \uc5f4\ud48d \u201c\uc5ed\uc8fc\ud589 \uc544\uc774\ucf58 \uc591\uc900\uc77c \ub204\uad6c?\u201d|date=2019-12-26|website=\uc774\uc288\uc778\ud329\ud2b8|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Yang dropped out to debut as a singer in Korea in 1990. He entered Korea in the same year and studied Korean at the [https://www.yskli.com/ Yonsei Korean Language Institute].\n\nYang debuted in March 1991 at the age of 21 with the album, \"Winter Traveller(\uaca8\uc6b8 \ub098\uadf8\ub124)\". A few months later, he returned to Los Angeles to work on his 2 album. His 2nd full length album was released in 1992. He released other hit songs like \"Dance with Me Miss\" (1992) and \"GaNaDaRaMaBaSa\" (1992).<ref name=\"koreatimes\" /><ref name=\"koreajoongangdaily\" /><ref name=\"yonhap\" />\n\nHe was credited as the first pop musician to introduce Korean audiences to the [[new jack swing]] genre, which was popular in the mid-1980s and early 1990s in the U.S. \n\nActive in South Korea from 1991 to 1993, he suddenly disappeared from the public scene and returned to the U.S. In a 2019 interview with the [[The Korea Times]], he revealed that \"he was hated by many for his unusual looks and songs.\" Some also threw rocks during his performance at an open-air stage. While a 10-year visa he held in Korea as a U.S. national had to be recertified every six months, he was denied an extension to his visa for no reason by an official at the Immigration Office. His nationality as an American also made it hard for him to gain acceptance in South Korea.\n\nIn 2001, he made another debut as JIY, a member of a music band V2, with a third album \"Fantasy\". V2 meant his \"Version 2\". He was in active under the name of JIY instead of his real name, Yang Joon-il. He lied about his age and made a big change in his look.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/?3860343|title='\ubc30\ucca0\uc218 \uc7bc' \uc591\uc900\uc77c, \ud5d8\ub09c\ud588\ub358 \uc778\uc0dd\uc0ac\u2192\uc2e0\ub4dc\ub86c\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc194\uc9c1 \uace0\ubc31\uae4c\uc9c0(\uc885\ud569)|date=2020-03-02|website=\ub274\uc2a41|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He hid his true identity as music producers told him he would not make it again due to his previous controversial image in Korea. His new song \"Fantasy\", composed by Valery Gaina of [[Cruise (band)|Cruise]], enjoyed a brief popularity before he finally put an end to his music career. Due to the agency's circumstances, it became impossible to work as a musician and after that he worked as an English teacher for 14 years.  In 2015, he returned to the United States. Because of his age, he had a hard time finding work. He worked as a warehouse worker, office cleaner, and restaurant server.    \n\nIn 2019, he gained attention through [[JTBC]]'s ''[[Two Yoo Project Sugar Man]]'', a program dedicated to finding and rediscovering old singers from the past. He sang \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WGIndlf_xU4&t=64s Rebecca]\", [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QU462sGMclc \"GaNaDaRaMaBaSa\", \"Dance With Me Miss\"], and \"Fantasy\". Still slim in figure and soulful in his performance, he dazzled the audience and show hosts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/03/682_280113.html|title=Yang Joon-il, a musician living ahead of his time, finally recognized 30 year later|date=2019-12-10|website=koreatimes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> When asked his next plans amid this viral syndrome, he simply said: \"I don't make any plans; I just focus on fully living every moment. If there's any plans, I hope to live as a humble husband and dad.\" When the show hosts asked him to give a message to 20-year-old himself living 30 years ago, Yang said: \"I know nothing will happen how you want. But don't worry, everything will come out perfectly in the end.\"<ref name=\"koreatimes\" /> After his fame skyrocketed again after his appearance on the show, he quit his job at the restaurant to focus on his entertainment career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2019/12/g-dragon-of-the-90s-yang-joon-il-visits-jtbcs-news-room-after-his-surging-popularity-says-he-was-working-at-a-restaurant-in-florida|title='G-Dragon of the 90s' Yang Joon Il visits JTBC's 'News Room' after his surging popularity, says he was working at a restaurant in Florida|website=allkpop|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> \n\nOn December 25, Christmas Day, he appeared on [[JTBC Newsroom]]. He said \"It's like a dream every day\", \"I've been trying to get rid of my prejudice against myself, which is full of my mind as if I had to abandon my unhappiness before I was happy.\"  \"There are no more tears\" Yang said, adding that his powerful fandom, which claims to be a support group, is also a big boost to Yang.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.habkorea.net/celebrity-of-celebrity-yang-joon-il-syndrome-in-korea/|title=Celebrity of celebrity, Yang Joon-il Syndrome in Korea {{!}} HaB Korea.net|date=2019-12-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> \n\nOn December 31, Yang met with fans through two official fan meeting events. \"Are you really here to see me?\"he said, tearing up with joy. \"This is my first time. I didn't imagine any of this. I'm so grateful.\"<ref name=\":1\" />  In a press conference at a fan meeting, he revealed that his sole dream of becoming a K-pop star in his 20s was finally accomplished now, at age 50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191231006300315|title=Return of long-forgotten singer Yang Joon-il brings middle-aged fans to music scene|last=\ubc15\ubcf4\ub78c|date=2019-12-31|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nJust a few days before the fan meeting he shot a commercial with Lotte Home Shopping<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allkpop.com/article/2019/12/gd-of-the-90s-yang-joon-il-lands-a-lotte-home-shopping-cf|title='GD of the 90's Yang Joon Il lands a Lotte Home Shopping CF|website=allkpop|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> for the first time in his life. He spent that money to rent an apartment in Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/ko-kr/entertainment/news/%ED%95%B4%ED%88%AC4-%EC%96%91%EC%A4%80%EC%9D%BC-%E2%80%9C%EC%83%9D%EC%95%A0-%EC%B2%AB-%EA%B4%91%EA%B3%A0%EB%AA%A8%EB%8D%B8%EB%A3%8C-%EB%B0%9B%EC%95%84-%E9%9F%93%EC%95%84%ED%8C%8C%ED%8A%B8-%EB%B3%B4%EC%A6%9D%EA%B8%88-%EB%A7%88%EB%A0%A8%E2%80%9D/ar-BB1166VA|title=\u2018\ud574\ud22c4\u2019 \uc591\uc900\uc77c \u201c\uc0dd\uc560 \uccab \uad11\uace0\ubaa8\ub378\ub8cc \ubc1b\uc544 \u97d3\uc544\ud30c\ud2b8 \ubcf4\uc99d\uae08 \ub9c8\ub828\u201d|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3 in 2020, Yang created his account on [[Instagram]].[https://www.instagram.com/jiytime/?hl=ko jiytime] On the 4th, he performed his debut song \"Rebecca\" on [[MBC TV|MBC]]'s \"[[Show! Music Core]]\" after 28 years after his debut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/04/732_281557.html|title=At 50, forgotten Korean-American singer compares to G-Dragon|date=2020-01-08|website=koreatimes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Yang appeared himself a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=buy_iFyS8Hg fan video], a parody of his own 90's fashion style.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=inogwFkBgY4 interview] JTBC's special feature <Sugar Man, Yang Joon-il, 91.19> aired on the 16th and 23rd. The title of the program is meant to commemorate his debut year, 1991 and 2019 when he was recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hundredkorea.com/en/2020/01/15/jtbc-%ec%8b%a0%eb%85%84-%ed%8a%b9%ec%a7%91-%eb%b0%a9%ec%86%a1-%ec%8a%88%ea%b0%80%eb%a7%a8-%ec%96%91%ec%a4%80%ec%9d%bc-91-19-%ec%a0%84%ea%b2%a9-%ed%8c%8c%ea%b2%a9-%ed%8e%b8%ec%84%b1/|title=JTBC set to air a variety special focused on Yang Joon Il|last=100KOREA|date=2020-01-15|website=100KOREA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn Febraury 3, his photo essay [Yang Joon Il Maybe] started a pre-sale. On the first day, over 15,000 copies were pre-sold and it became bestseller. A series of the interviews with the behind-the-scenes of photo shooting for his book was released also.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C3qzBsWHvic interview-Question From Yang Joon Il] On the 9th, Yang opened his official YouTube channel, [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWagJUPy0iR5Cf8hafiYM-w Official Yang Joon Il]. The number of subscribers has spiked up to over 15K in a single day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allkpop.com/video/2020/02/yang-joon-il-opens-up-his-official-youtube-channel|title=Yang Joon Il opens up his official YouTube channel!|website=allkpop|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> On Valentine's day, on Febraury 14, [Yang Joon Il Maybe] was officially released.  \n\nOn March 14, the 100th day anniversary of his re-debut, Yang and choreographer Lia Kim appeared on MBC \"[[Show! Music Core]]\" of the via a collaboration stage. Two of them went on satage with his song \"Dance with Me\" released in 1992.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=degunNXQVtA practice video version]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://star.mt.co.kr/foreign/starViewEng.html?no=2020031502086982284|title=Yang Jun Il X Lia Kim, Collaboration Stage Steals the Scene|last=MoneyToday|website=star.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> On the 16th, Yang was shown as a lecturer on \"Sebasi Talk\". The title of the lecture was <Message to unhappy people in competition>. It hit 1 million view mark in 2 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nocutnews.co.kr/news/5310124|title='\uc138\ubc14\uc2dc'\uc591\uc900\uc77c \uac15\uc5f0\uc758 \ud765\ud589, \uc608\ub2a5\uc744 \ub6f0\uc5b4\ub118\ub294 \uad50\uc591 \ucf58\ud150\uce20\ub85c\uc11c \uac00\uce58 \uc99d\uba85|last=\uc138\ubc14\uc2dc \uc5d0\ub514\ud130 J|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=March 17, 2020|access-date=}}</ref>   \n\nHe also plans to re-arrange and re-record his old songs to release a repackaged album. After that, he hopes to release new songs.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Album===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\uaca8\uc6b8 \ub098\uadf8\ub124(1991) - produced by Lee Beom-hee(\uc774\ubc94\ud76c)\n!title\n!written by\n!composed by\n!length\n|-\n|\uaca8\uc6b8 \ub098\uadf8\ub124\n|\uc774\uc0c1\ub9cc\n|Lee Beom-hee(\uc774\ubc94\ud76c)\n|3:29\n|-\n|\ud5ec\ud504 \ubbf8 \ud050\ud54f [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CFemlEChrcE Help me, Cupid!]\n|\uac15\ub355\ud76c\n|Lee Beom-hee(\uc774\ubc94\ud76c)\n|3:46\n|-\n|